            "description": "Selecting appropriate outlet specification and creating secure wire connections ensures reliable performance and electrical safety. Outlet selection considers intended application—standard 15A or 20A outlets for general use, GFCI outlets for wet locations and outdoor areas, tamper-resistant outlets for child safety (code requirement for all 15A/20A outlets in dwelling units), weather-resistant outlets for outdoor exposure, hospital-grade outlets for critical equipment, USB combination outlets for charging convenience, and smart outlets for automation. Commercial-grade outlets (specified as \"spec-grade\") provide superior contact retention and longevity (100,000+ insertion cycles versus 15,000 for residential-grade outlets), recommended for frequently-used locations. Wire termination using screw terminals provides most reliable connections—stripping wire insulation 3/4 inch, forming hook shape wrapping clockwise around screw terminal (same direction screw tightens), and tightening screw to 12 in-lb torque (specified in outlet instructions). Backstab connections (push-in terminals on back of outlets) are not recommended—they create high-resistance connections loosening over time and causing overheating and arcing. Pigtail connections required when circuit continues to additional outlets downstream—short wire section connecting outlet to main circuit wires using twist-on wire connectors, preventing circuit interruption if outlet fails or needs replacement. Color coding connections includes black (hot) wire to brass-colored screw terminals, white (neutral) wire to silver-colored screw terminals, and bare or green (ground) wire to green ground screw. Reversed connections (hot and neutral swapped) create shock hazards and potential equipment damage. Our electricians verify correct polarity during testing phase.",
