        "content": "These symptoms indicate developing electrical problems that should be addressed promptly to prevent safety hazards or complete failure. Dead outlets on circuit: multiple outlets on same circuit not working indicates circuit breaker trip, GFCI trip protecting downstream outlets, or wiring problem affecting circuit—requires professional diagnosis identifying whether breaker/GFCI reset solves problem or [link:/services/electrical-repair-tucson|electrical repair] needed. Loose or wobbly outlets and switches: outlets or switches physically loose in wall or wiggling when plugging in devices indicates deteriorated mounting or damaged electrical box—creates fire risk from wire movement causing connection loosening. Outlets not holding plugs securely: plugs falling out of outlets or requiring effort to insert indicates worn outlet contacts failing to grip plug prongs properly—worn outlets present arcing and fire hazards plus frustration from devices disconnecting unexpectedly. Two-prong ungrounded outlets: older outlets lacking ground pin (two-prong instead of three-prong) present shock hazards and can't protect sensitive electronics—particularly dangerous in kitchens, bathrooms, garages, and outdoor locations where GFCI protection is required by code. Flickering lights when using outlets: lights dimming or flickering when plugging in appliances or devices indicates inadequate circuit capacity, loose connections, or voltage drop from undersized wiring—professional load analysis determines whether circuit upgrade needed. Switches requiring extra force to operate: light switches sticking, requiring unusual force, or not staying in position indicate deteriorated switch mechanism—internal contact failure creates arcing and fire risk. Frequent GFCI tripping: GFCI outlets that trip frequently (multiple times per week) during normal use indicate either actual ground fault condition requiring diagnosis or sensitive GFCI requiring replacement with more stable model. Missing GFCI protection in required locations: bathrooms, kitchens, outdoor areas, and garages require GFCI protection by electrical code—missing protection presents shock hazards and home sale complications from code violations. Schedule professional service within 24-48 hours for thorough diagnosis and code-compliant repairs."
