        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": "Electrocution and severe shock hazards: According to the Consumer Product Safety Commission (CPSC), electrical accidents kill approximately 400 Americans annually and injure 4,000 more, with significant percentages involving DIY electrical work. Improper power shutdown procedures (failing to verify power disconnection with voltage tester, shutting off wrong circuit breaker, or assuming power is off without testing) create lethal shock risks. Fire hazards from improper installation: National Fire Protection Association (NFPA) data indicates electrical failures and malfunctions cause an estimated 45,210 home fires annually, with loose connections being a leading cause. DIY installation mistakes creating fire risks include loose wire connections generating resistance heat and arcing, reversed polarity (hot and neutral wires swapped) causing equipment damage and shock hazards, inadequate box fill (overcrowded electrical boxes) creating heat buildup and contact with flammable materials, backstab connections instead of screw terminals leading to loosening over time, missing or improper grounding allowing dangerous voltage on metal appliance cases, and aluminum wiring connections without proper techniques and CO/ALR rated devices. Code violations affecting home sales and insurance: DIY installations frequently fail to meet National Electrical Code (NEC) requirements and local Tucson amendments, creating complications during home sales when inspectors identify violations requiring correction before closing. Missing GFCI protection in required locations (bathrooms, kitchens, outdoor areas, garages), inadequate AFCI protection in bedroom circuits, improper box installation (boxes recessed behind wall surface creating fire spread risk), non-tamper-resistant outlets in dwelling units (code requirement since 2008), and unpermitted electrical work can void homeowner's insurance coverage for electrical-related claims and losses. Expensive correction costs: Professional electricians frequently encounter DIY electrical work requiring complete reinstallation—reversed polarity requiring rewiring, backstab connections requiring replacement with proper screw terminal connections, undersized electrical boxes requiring box replacement to meet fill requirements, and improper GFCI wiring requiring complete rewiring to function correctly. Cost of correcting failed DIY installations typically exceeds 150-200% of original professional installation cost due to diagnostic time, correction of multiple errors, and potential damage to surrounding areas."
