        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": "GFCI outlet testing: Press TEST button on all GFCI outlets monthly to verify proper function—outlet should immediately trip cutting power. Press RESET button to restore power. If GFCI fails to trip when TEST pressed or won't reset afterward, replace outlet immediately as it's no longer providing shock protection. Test GFCIs after electrical storms or power outages as power surges can damage GFCI circuitry without obvious symptoms. Visual inspection for damage: Check outlets and switches for physical damage including cracks in outlet or switch bodies, melted or discolored plastic, charring or burn marks on outlet faces or surrounding walls, missing or damaged faceplates, and loose outlets or switches wobbling in wall. Replace damaged devices immediately—physical damage often indicates internal failure creating fire and shock hazards. Listen for unusual sounds: While using outlets and switches, listen for buzzing, humming, crackling, or sizzling sounds indicating loose connections or arcing. Any audible electrical noises from outlets or switches require immediate professional evaluation. Check for proper outlet grip: Periodically test whether outlets hold plugs securely without falling out. Worn outlet contacts failing to grip plug prongs indicate outlet replacement needed—loose connections create arcing and fire risks plus frustration from devices disconnecting. Verify switch operation: Test light switches for smooth, positive operation without sticking, requiring extra force, or failing to stay in position. Switches requiring unusual effort or exhibiting erratic operation indicate internal contact deterioration requiring replacement. Infrared temperature checks (if available): If you have infrared thermometer or thermal imaging camera, check outlet and switch temperatures during use. Temperatures exceeding 100°F (above ambient room temperature) indicate overheating from loose connections or overloaded circuits requiring professional diagnosis."
