        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": "Understanding proper outlet and switch usage prevents premature failure and maintains electrical safety. Avoid overloading outlets: Each 15-amp circuit supports 1,800 watts maximum (with 20% safety margin reducing practical limit to 1,440 watts), each 20-amp circuit supports 2,400 watts maximum (1,920 watts practical limit with safety margin). Common appliance loads include space heaters 1,500W, hair dryers 1,800W, microwave ovens 1,000-1,500W, coffee makers 800-1,200W, and toasters 800-1,500W. Using multiple high-wattage devices on same circuit causes overload even if multiple outlets available on circuit. Gentle plug insertion and removal: Insert plugs straight into outlets without forcing or twisting—misaligned insertion damages outlet contacts accelerating wear. Remove plugs by gripping plug body, never by pulling on cord which stresses internal connections in both plug and outlet. Frequent rapid plug cycling accelerates outlet contact wear—minimize unnecessary plugging and unplugging when possible. Appropriate plug types for outlets: Never force three-prong grounded plugs into two-prong ungrounded outlets using adapters without proper grounding—defeats ground protection and creates shock hazards. Use properly rated plugs for circuits—15-amp plugs for 15-amp circuits, 20-amp plugs (with perpendicular blade) for 20-amp circuits. Switch ratings and loads: Standard light switches rated for 15 amps resistive load can't safely control high-inrush loads like large motors without arc suppression. Dimmer switches have lower maximum ratings than standard switches—typical 600W for incandescent dimmers, 150-300W for LED dimmers—verify total load doesn't exceed dimmer rating. Outdoor outlet protection: Close weatherproof covers when outdoor outlets not in use protecting against moisture infiltration and insect nesting. Verify \"in-use\" covers protecting outlets even when cords plugged in—rain water entering outlets causes dangerous ground faults and GFCI tripping. Remove outdoor extension cords when not needed preventing moisture exposure to outlet connections. GFCI outlet considerations: GFCI outlets protect from ground faults but may trip when certain tools and appliances create small normal ground leakage—vintage refrigerators, long extension cords, some power tools. If GFCI trips consistently when using specific device, verify device isn't actually faulty (have it tested by qualified repair technician) before assuming nuisance tripping. Following proper usage guidelines extends outlet and switch lifespan from typical 15-20 years to 25+ years while maintaining safety throughout service life."
